{"id":"2202.05537","submitter":"Zafer Dursunkaya","authors":"Goksel Yuncu and Yigit Akkus and Zafer Dursunkaya","title":"Interplay of capillary and Marangoni flows in micropillar evaporation","comments":null,"journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"physics.flu-dyn physics.app-ph","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  The evaporation from a micropillar evaporator is a problem governed by\nvarious interfacial phenomena such as the capillarity-induced liquid flow,\nthin-film evaporation intensifying near the contact lines, and\nthermocapillarity-induced Marangoni flow. However, past research has not been\nable to assess the effect of Marangoni flow due to the missing coupling between\ncell- and device-level modeling. In this work, we develop a comprehensive model\nfor the evaporation from a micropillar evaporator by coupling the liquid flow\nwith the energy transfer in both liquid and solid domains at both cell- and\ndevice-levels. The model is successfully validated with previous experiments.\nWhen the Marangoni number is sufficiently high, the model identifies a sharp\nreduction in the evaporator temperature attributed to the thermocapillary\nconvection creating circulations beneath the liquid-vapor interface, which\nresults in the formation of periodic reverse surface flows on the interface.\nThis temperature drop cannot be identified when thermocapillarity is switched\noff in the model and the model's prediction substantially deviates from\nexperimental measurement. Therefore, the current study reveals a hitherto\nunexplored role of Marangoni flow in the evaporation of water from micropillar\nevaporators.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Fri, 11 Feb 2022 10:25:25 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Wed, 23 Mar 2022 14:16:11 GMT"}],"update_date":"2022-03-24"}
